Philippine Stock Movers: Lepanto, MRC, Philippine Long Distance

-- B y   I a n   C .   S a y s o n
-- 
2011-06-15T04:39:19Z

-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2011-06-15/mrc-pal-philippine-telephone-philippine-stocks-preview.html
Shares of the following companies
had unusual moves in Philippine trading. Stock symbols are in
parentheses and prices are as of the noon close in  Manila .  The Philippine Stock Exchange Index rallied 1.5 percent to
4,201.38, the steepest advance since April 4, after Moody’s
Investors Service said it raised the nation’s credit rating.  Metals producers:  Lepanto Consolidated Mining (LC)  Co.’s Class B
shares (LCB PM), which have no ownership restrictions, jumped
9.5 percent to 1.04 pesos, the sharpest advance since May 18
after gold and copper prices gained.  Philex Mining Corp. (PX)  , the nation’s largest metals producer, added 1.9 percent to
19.10 pesos, snapping a six-day slump.  Copper for delivery in three months rallied 2.9 percent on
the London Metal Exchange yesterday, the steepest increase since
May 18. Gold for immediate delivery rose for a second day,
advancing as much as 0.4 percent.  International Container Terminal Services Inc. (ICT)  ,
the largest Philippine port operator, added 1 percent to 50.50
pesos. The stock earlier climbed as much as 3.6 percent after
the company said it set up a unit in preparation for the signing
of a contract to manage a facility in Subic, north of Manila.  MRC Allied Inc. (MRC)  , a property developer, sank 15
percent to 57 centavos, the largest loss since Jan. 8, 2010. A
lock-up period on 3.12 billion MRC Allied shares has expired and
the stock will be eligible for trading from today, the
Philippine Stock Exchange said on its website.  Philippine Long Distance Telephone Co. (TEL)  , the
nation’s largest phone company, climbed 1.9 percent to 2,348
pesos, the sharpest advance since June 1. The company will
maintain its dividend policy and its purchase of a rival will
have a “modest” impact on  cash flow , Chairman Manuel Pangilinan said.  To contact the reporter on this story:
Ian C. Sayson in Manila at 
 isayson@bloomberg.net   To contact the editor responsible for this story:
